<doc id="1243451" wikidata="Q2421733" url="?curid=1243451" title="Thom space">
<text>In mathematics, the Thom space, Thom complex, or Pontryagin–Thom construction (named after René Thom and Lev Pontryagin) of algebraic topology and differential topology is a topological space associated to a vector bundle, over any paracompact space.

==Construction of the Thom space==

One way to construct this space is as follows. Let

:formula_1

be a rank &quot;n&quot; real vector bundle over the paracompact space &quot;B&quot;. Then for each point &quot;b&quot; in &quot;B&quot;, the fiber formula_2 is an &quot;n&quot;-dimensional real vector space. We can form an &quot;n&quot;-sphere bundle formula_3 by taking the one-point compactification of each fiber and gluing them together to get the total space. Finally, from the total space formula_4 we obtain the Thom space formula_5 as the quotient of formula_4 by &quot;B&quot;; that is, by identifying all the new points to a single point formula_7, which we take as the basepoint of formula_5. If &quot;B&quot; is compact, then formula_5 is the one-point compactification of &quot;E&quot;.

For example, if &quot;E&quot; is the trivial bundle formula_10, then formula_4 is formula_12 and, writing formula_13 for &quot;B&quot; with a disjoint basepoint, formula_5 is the smash product of formula_13 and formula_16; that is, the &quot;n&quot;-th reduced suspension of formula_13.

Alternatively, since &quot;B&quot; is paracompact, &quot;E&quot; can be given a Euclidean metric and then formula_5 can be defined as the quotient of the unit disk bundle of &quot;E&quot; by the unit formula_19-sphere bundle of &quot;E&quot;.

==The Thom isomorphism==

The significance of this construction begins with the following result, which belongs to the subject of cohomology of fiber bundles. (We have stated the result in terms of formula_20 coefficients to avoid complications arising from orientability; see also Orientation of a vector bundle#Thom space.)

Let formula_21 be a real vector bundle of rank &quot;n&quot;. Then there is an isomorphism called a Thom isomorphism
:formula_22
for all &quot;k&quot; greater than or equal to 0, where the right hand side is reduced cohomology.

This theorem was formulated and proved by René Thom in his famous 1952 thesis.

We can interpret the theorem as a global generalization of the suspension isomorphism on local trivializations, because the Thom space of a trivial bundle on &quot;B&quot; of rank &quot;k&quot; is isomorphic to the &quot;k&quot;th suspension of formula_13, &quot;B&quot; with a disjoint point added (cf. #Construction of the Thom space.) This can be more easily seen in the formulation of the theorem that does not make reference to Thom space:

In concise terms, the last part of the theorem says that &quot;u&quot; freely generates formula_24 as a right formula_25-module. The class &quot;u&quot; is usually called the Thom class of &quot;E&quot;. Since the pullback formula_26 is a ring isomorphism, formula_27 is given by the equation:

:formula_28

In particular, the Thom isomorphism sends the identity element of formula_29 to &quot;u&quot;. Note: for this formula to make sense, &quot;u&quot; is treated as an element of (we drop the ring formula_30)

:formula_31

The standard reference for the Thom isomorphism is the book by Bott and Tu.

==Significance of Thom&#x27;s work==

In his 1952 paper, Thom showed that the Thom class, the Stiefel–Whitney classes, and the Steenrod operations were all related. He used these ideas to prove in the 1954 paper &quot;Quelques propriétés globales des variétés differentiables&quot; that the cobordism groups could be computed as the homotopy groups of certain Thom spaces &quot;MG&quot;(&quot;n&quot;). The proof depends on and is intimately related to the transversality properties of smooth manifolds—see Thom transversality theorem. By reversing this construction, John Milnor and Sergei Novikov (among many others) were able to answer questions about the existence and uniqueness of high-dimensional manifolds: this is now known as surgery theory. In addition, the spaces &quot;MG(n)&quot; fit together to form spectra &quot;MG&quot; now known as Thom spectra, and the cobordism groups are in fact stable. Thom&#x27;s construction thus also unifies differential topology and stable homotopy theory, and is in particular integral to our knowledge of the stable homotopy groups of spheres.

If the Steenrod operations are available, we can use them and the isomorphism of the theorem to construct the Stiefel–Whitney classes. Recall that the Steenrod operations (mod 2) are natural transformations

:formula_32

defined for all nonnegative integers &quot;m&quot;. If formula_33, then formula_34 coincides with the cup square. We can define the &quot;i&quot;th Stiefel–Whitney class formula_35 of the vector bundle formula_21 by:

:formula_37

==Consequences for differentiable manifolds==

If we take the bundle in the above to be the tangent bundle of a smooth manifold, the conclusion of the above is called the Wu formula, and has the following strong consequence: since the Steenrod operations are invariant under homotopy equivalence, we conclude that the Stiefel–Whitney classes of a manifold are as well. This is an extraordinary result that does not generalize to other characteristic classes. There exists a similar famous and difficult result establishing topological invariance for rational Pontryagin classes, due to Sergei Novikov.

==Thom spectrum==

=== Real cobordism ===
There are two ways to think about bordism: one as considering two formula_38-manifolds formula_39 are cobordant if there is an formula_40-manifold with boundary formula_41 such that

:formula_42

Another technique to encode this kind of information is to take an embedding formula_43 and considering the normal bundle

:formula_44

The embedded manifold together with the isomorphism class of the normal bundle actually encodes the same information as the cobordism class formula_45. This can be shown by using a cobordism formula_41 and finding an embedding to some formula_47 which gives a homotopy class of maps to the Thom space formula_48 defined below. Showing the isomorphism of

:formula_49

requires a little more work.

=== Definition of Thom spectrum ===
By definition, the Thom spectrum is a sequence of Thom spaces

:formula_50

where we wrote formula_51 for the universal vector bundle of rank &quot;n&quot;. The sequence forms a spectrum. A theorem of Thom says that formula_52 is the unoriented cobordism ring; the proof of this theorem relies crucially on Thom’s transversality theorem. The lack of transversality requires that alternative methods be found to compute cobordism rings of, say, topological manifolds from Thom spectra.

